# Next.js Architecture & Performance

Use modern Next.js App Router architecture. Prioritize server rendering, performance, reduced client JavaScript, clear rendering boundaries, and scalable async architecture. Avoid legacy Pages Router mentality.

---

# 1. Server Components First

Use Server Components by default.
- Ideal for data fetching, async rendering, security, performance, and reducing client JavaScript.
- Avoid converting entire trees into client components unnecessarily.

---

# 2. Client Components & Boundaries

Use Client Components (`"use client"`) ONLY when interaction is required.
- Valid cases: event handlers, browser APIs, local interactive state, animations, refs, effects.
- Keep client boundaries small (push them as far down the tree as possible).
- Avoid leaking client-side rendering into large server trees.
- Static domain catalogs and read-only data: prefer Server Components with serialized props when there is no client-only dependency.

---

# 3. Data Fetching & Async Architecture

Prefer server-side data fetching whenever possible.
- Use Server Components, Server Actions, or Route Handlers.
- Avoid unnecessary client-side fetching for critical data (e.g. `useEffect(() => fetch(...), [])`).
- Design async flows intentionally (consider loading states, suspense, streaming, retries, invalidation, error boundaries).

---

# 4. Server Actions & Route Handlers

- **Server Actions:** Use for mutations when appropriate (forms, secure operations). Domain mutations belong in `actions/` (see global-architecture.mdc §2.3). Keep mutation logic outside UI components. Avoid large mutation flows directly inside client components.
- **Server reads:** Use `queries/` for server-side data fetching (see `global-architecture.mdc` §2.3). Prefer `server.ts` as the public server surface when exposing queries/actions externally. Server-state and cache policy: see `state-and-reactivity.mdc` §4.
- **Route Handlers (`app/api/`):** Keep API logic isolated. Validate inputs, orchestrate requests, isolate transport logic. Avoid mixing API logic into UI layers.

---

# 5. Rendering & Caching Strategies

- Choose rendering strategies (static, dynamic, streaming, partial hydration) based on actual feature requirements. Avoid making everything dynamic by default.
- Understand caching behaviors (static, dynamic, revalidated, uncached).
- Use layouts intentionally (persistent navigation, shared UI shells). Avoid duplicated layout structures across pages.

---

# 6. Performance Optimization

- Reduce unnecessary client JavaScript (prefer server rendering, streaming).
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders (use derived UI, keep state local).
- Lazy load heavy interactive components.
- Keep bundle size minimal; avoid shipping unused JavaScript.
- Optimize images and fonts.
- Avoid large client-side state trees.
- Measure performance before optimizing; avoid premature optimization.

---

# 7. Error Handling & Loading

- Use proper error boundaries (`error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`). Avoid ad-hoc error handling scattered everywhere.
- Loading states should be intentional and reusable. Prefer suspense, route `loading.tsx`, or reusable async boundaries instead of repeating `if (loading) return <Loading />` everywhere.
